<dl id="n54127c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54127c">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54127c"> 127(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> crystalisation <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54127c"><li>FW 86.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n54127c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n54127c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54127c">MS BL 47476a-194</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:409 <a name="dd10" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n54127c">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Carefully notice what separates out. You will see that the colourless crystals of alum are formed, and side by side with them blue crystals of sulphate of copper appear. The two different salts can thus be separated by <mark>crystallization</mark>; and if we took time enough, we could pick out all the alum crystals and put them on one side, leaving all the crystals of sulphate of copper. This shows how nature separates out things which are different, and we see that many rocks and minerals are formed in the earth by crystallization. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC1"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 49</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
